	<h2 id="What-is-the-source-of-your-project-information">What is the source of your project information?<a href="#What-is-the-source-of-your-project-information" class="wiki-anchor"></a></h2>


	<p>Project documentation used by Geo-coders is publicly available through The World Bank Projects &#38; Operations Portal</p>


	<p>The World Bank carries out projects and provides a wide variety of analytical and advisory services to help meet the development needs of individual countries and the international community. Summary operational reports are provided in the Portal.</p>


	<p>The following data has been obtained from this source:</p>


	<p><strong>Project Counts</strong><br />The total number of active projects at the first and second sub-national levels e.g. provinces, departments, districts, municipalities.</p>


	<p><strong>Project Locations</strong><br />The maps by sector display the number of locations of a given World Bank project. For example a project in health may have different hospital locations; the Project Locations layer will show all these locations on the map</p>


	<p>Project locations of planned activities according to the project documentation (i.e. Project Appraisal Document, Environmental Assessment, Integrated Safeguard Data Sheet) were used to geo-code the project’s locations. While this information has been publicly available through the Bank’s project database, the Mapping for Results Platform makes this information easily accessible and increases transparency and accountability. In cases where little project documentation or location information is available, project task leaders were contacted to request additional location information.</p>


