	<h2 id="How-precise-are-the-project-locations-shown-in-your-maps">How precise are the project locations shown in your maps?<a href="#How-precise-are-the-project-locations-shown-in-your-maps" class="wiki-anchor"></a></h2>


	<p>The Mapping for Results platform is being launched as a beta version, since we are currently working on enhancing the availability of geo-coded project locations across all Bank projects. For now, the precision of each project is dependent on the quality of the available project documentation, since a standardized reporting mechanism for the locations of Bank projects is currently still under development. Thus, sources vary in the precision dependent on the available data currently being reported in the project documentation. For most projects the locations are being reported; however sometimes the exact location is not available, and instead the general project area (i.e. region or districts) is reported. The system of georeferencing used by the World Bank copes with coordinates in four main levels, ranging from point locations, through two administrative divisions, to the country level.</p>


	<h2 id="How-can-I-tell-what-each-point-represents">How can I tell what each point represents?<a href="#How-can-I-tell-what-each-point-represents" class="wiki-anchor"></a></h2>


	<p>Eight precision categories are connected to the coordinates in order for researchers to select subsets of the dataset that contain different levels of precision. When selecting a single project location point, a window will appear including a description of the precision of that location.</p>


